Daughter of Michael Hoke Smith, 
  <a href="http://www.geni.com/people/M-Hoke-Smith/362769088550012804" rel="nofollow">www.geni.com/people/M-Hoke-Smith/362769088550012804</a>
&quot;Hoke Smith (1855-1931): Smith was a lawyer and Democratic politician from Atlanta, Georgia. President Grover Cleveland appointed him secretary of the interior in 1893. Smith was elected governor of Georgia in 1907 and served until 1911 when he was elected to the U.S. Senate. He served in the senate until 1921. &quot;

In 1914, Callie was one of the leaders of a group promoting the cotton industry through a &quot;cotton bargain day.&quot;
  <a href="http://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F20F13F63A5B13738DDDA80A94D1405B848DF1D3&amp;scp=2&amp;sq=Callie%20Hoke%20Smith&amp;st=cse" rel="nofollow">query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F20F13F63A5B13738...</a>
 WASHINGTON, Sept. 20. -- The idea of stimulating interest in the cotton industries by having a nation-wide bargain day in cotton goods and a cotton fashion show in Washington seems to have taken hold. Many women whose husbands or fathers are prominent in national affairs indorsed the scheme today, and meetings will be held this week to arrange the details.
